-- 1. Stork Moon
UPDATE poems SET
  content = 'There is a stork on the top of this ancient palace
wall that laid a moon in its nest like an egg.
The sultan declared it a national monument
but the people said let it be and time unraveled
and wars were fought and the sultan died
and his son was inaugurated while hands clapped
in the plaza and snake charmers played flute songs
and tourism tripled and the straw of the nest blew away
in the strong Sahara winds. The walls of the palace shrank
into museum walls, adorned with memorabilia,
and when the stork returned with silver fish for its baby
moon, it found a vacant wall
and the habitat unrecognisably gentrified.
The new sultan had come to a compromise
with the people, for he was wise, and had encased
the moon in glass, and set it in orbit, just outside the atmosphere
so that all could see, on this night or another: a gift
to make all his subjects content. And they all were, all except the stork
who, to this day, flies from palace to palace, seeking something
disappeared, gliding over the face of the water, with stretched wings
and the glimmering reflection of the moon under its feathery belly
(a shadow of the heart).',
  plain_text = 'There is a stork on the top of this ancient palace
wall that laid a moon in its nest like an egg.
